    <title>Guide: using attestations (Devcon ticket example)</title>
    <body>
        <p>Conceptually, TokenScripts treats ticket attestation as a Token. It does not matter if a
            Token exists on the blockchain as a ERC20 or ERC721 token, it is a token in TokenScript
            terms as long as it is usable as a Token. In this case, since the holder of ticket
            attestations can use it for web authentication as well as smart contract functions such
            as voting, for practical purpose it is a Token.</p>
        <p>We will use Devcon ticket as an example and build a few websites around it: </p>
        <ol id="ol_dwl_cgd_ynb">
            <li><xref href="issuer-site.dita">Issuer's website</xref></li>
            <li><xref href="3rd-party-site.dita">3rd party website</xref> which carries the capacity
                to access the token (attestation-based)</li>
            <li>3rd party website which  needs to authenticate the attestation's holder</li>
            <li>3rd website which allows the attestation to do some transactions</li>
        </ol>
